{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17499924","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17499924"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:05:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:05:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1586"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1586","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1586"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.09,0.11,0.73,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1586"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91446"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1586","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1586"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1586"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75117"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"849"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2369"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31252"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42347"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91446","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/91446"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 18-year-old woman wants these lesions on her hand removed. She initially had only one, but reports multiple others arising over the past few years. She reports similar lesions around her toes. She is irritated by them and picks at them absent mindedly, and is also self-conscious about their appearance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination there are several small cauliflower-like papules with rough papillomatous surfaces across the palmar surface. There is a crop of multiple lesions around her left thumb (Image).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Topical corticosteroids","5-fluorouracil cream","Imiquimod","Cryotherapy","Excision"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe picture shows multiple common warts, which could respond to treatment with \u003Cstrong\u003Ecryotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E. When performing cryotherapy for warts, treat with a 10-20 second freeze-thaw cycle and repeat every couple of weeks as needed. The patient should be advised about the risk of ulceration with aggressive cryotherapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETopical corticosteroids could accelerate the development of common warts. 5-fluorouracil cream and imiquimod are used for field treatment of multiple solar keratoses, or spot treatment if intraepidermal carcinoma and superficial basal cell carcinoma respectively. Imiquimod has been used to treat anogenital warts but is ineffective for cutaneous warts. Excision is not usually necessary and is not gold standard treatment due to scarring, pain and high rate of recurrence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther treatments proposed for warts (with varying efficacy) include topical salicylic acid, bleomycin injections, pulsed dye laser, photodynamic therapy and laser vaporisation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENo treatment is universally effective at eradicating viral warts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEven without any treatment, in children 50% of warts disappear within 6 months, and 90% resolve in 2 years. In adults viral warts are more persistant but usually clear eventually. Viral warts are more likely to recur in immunosuppressed patients and in individuals who smoke.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cryotherapy is the preferred treatment for warts."],"references":["Leung L. Treating common warts - options and evidence. Aust Fam Physician. 2010 Dec;39(12):933-7. PMID: 21301674."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75117"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1586"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18463"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18463","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18463"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/346a7262-6741-455d-bbc4-fe2b49da9684.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/346a7262-6741-455d-bbc4-fe2b49da9684.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":598}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75117","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75117"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-15T19:55:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-15T19:55:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1586"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91446"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only su